Quoted By:
>>14813050
>I think a lot of people don't want to write about the baggage they come with.
Personally I just see it as less than important when you're dealing with a medium that isn't as visual as art. When you describe a character as "part wolf, part fox" or something in a story, chances are the reader's probably going to just imagine them as one or the other. Even if you get more crazy with the mixes like "cat and bear", there will likely be traits of one of those two species that the reader focuses on more; they might visualize the feline features or the ursine features primarily unless the story keeps reminding you of what's unique about that character. Like, I'm going to keep picturing the cat/bear as a bear first and foremost with a stumpy tail unless you mention the longer tail occasionally.

I'll be the first to admit there's some spots where it was just sitting there for a while because I didn't know how to flow into the next section of text, and that example was definitely somewhat of one of them, although more for how Andrew leads in than anything else.
It might not come off as well as I read it in my head, but the way Gwen and Winnifred talk are completely different, with Gwen being much more "teenagery" and her mum being more old fashioned / having a commanding presence. Not quite sure how to fix that.
Having a absolute hatred of "And he said, and then this character exclaimed", the way dialog gets put down does rely a lot on paying attention to context, which I know doesn't always work perfectly.

Ordinarily I'd be laying the world building on kinda thick, or at least be incredibly defined from the get go on how things came to be, but for this I was going for both a longer narrative where a fair number of the details gets filled in along the way, and somewhat more of a "things happen because things happen" approach some story writers have when writing, both trying it as a challenge of sorts and because trying to explain how the eventual transformation goes down would more than likely break the attempt at a comfy vibe for the rest of the story, along with the nonchalant reaction of others around them, if that sort of thing were infectious 'n all.
